{
  "doc_id": "46522",
  "text": "In 2005 a group in Canada reported the effects of exercise training on glucose homeostasis in almost 600 subjects, using a standard IVGTT [CITATION_1] . While they observed a mean increase of 10% in insulin sensitivity after 20 weeks of aerobic training, between-subject variations in metabolic response to exercise were large, not unlike our study. In fact, most subjects showed a deterioration in the acute insulin response to glucose. It has been suggested that progressive resistance training confers greater metabolic benefits than aerobic training [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . While the exercise modality may also be relevant, most studies to date, including our own, have examined the effects of aerobic exercise training.",
